{ J. Polgar – F. Berkes, Budapest 2003 }
1. Rh7+ { White sacrifices a whole rook, just to bring her queen onto the open file with tempo. } 1... Kxh7 2. Qh2+ Kg8 { 2...Kg7  is even worse, on account of  3.Qh6+. } 3. Rh1 { The threat is Qh8# or Qh7#. Black must give up his queen to prevent mate. } 3... Bxg5+ 4. Nxg5 Qxg5+ { 4...Kg7  does not save the queen, because of  5.Nxe6+!  , and if  5...fxe6  then  6.Qh7+  Kf6  7.g5+!  Kxg5  8.Qh4#. } 5. f4 Qxf4+ 6. Qxf4 Bxe4 7. Qxe4 { But not  7.Qh6??  due to  7...Bxh1.  White has a decisive material and positional advantage. Black may have resigned too early here, but White should win in the long run. } *


