{ In order to achieve the goal of the combination, you often have to accept temporary material losses. When this is the case, you should not break off your calculation of lines too soon. The position can only be evaluated when there are no more active moves left.  In the examples which follow, we shall see once more how important the active moves are. Try to attack the opposing pieces!  J. Capablanca – A. Alekhine, World Ch, Buenos Aires  (1)  1927  (Variation from the game) }
1... Qc7 2. Rf8 { If  2.Qb3  Qxb8  3.Qxf7+  , then  3...Kh6–+  escapes the checks.   2.Ra8  would not be good, on account of  2...Qc6–+  , with an attack on the rook and also the threat of  Re1+. } 2... Kg7 3. Ra8 Re1+ { Or first  3...Qc6. } 4. Kh2 Qc6 { With a double attack, threatening the a8-rook as well as mate on h1. } *


